name: 2,5-bis-trichloromethyl-[1,3]dioxolan-4-one

A carbonyl group typically raises the melting point due to its capacity for hydrogen bonding and dipole-dipole interactions; we can estimate this as +20 degrees Celsius. Thus, starting from a base of 0 degrees Celsius for a simple 1,3-dioxolane, the adjustments would be as follows: Base melting point (0) + two trichloromethyl groups (2 * +30) + one carbonyl group (+20), which results in a predicted melting point increase of 80 degrees Celsius.
